{{Infobox language |name=Enu |altname=Ximoluo |states=China |region=Yunnan |ethnicity=[[Hani people|Hani]] |speakers=14,000 |date=2009 |ref=<ref>Jiang, et. al 2009</ref> |familycolor=Sino-Tibetan |fam2=([[Tibeto-Burman languages|Tibeto-Burman]]) |fam3=[[Lolo–Burmese languages|Lolo–Burmese]] |fam4=[[Loloish languages|Loloish]] |fam5=[[Southern Loloish languages|Southern]] |fam6=Bi-Ka |fam7=[[Piyo language|Piyo]] |iso3=enu |glotto=enuu1235 |glottorefname=Enu}}
'''Enu''' or '''Ximoluo''' ({{zh|西摩洛}}; autonym: ''{{IPA|ŋɔ31 ŋjv̩31}}'' (Jiang, et al. 2009:4)) is a [[Hanoish languages|Hanoish]] language of the Bi-Ka branch spoken by 14,000 people of the [[Hani people|Hani]] ethnic group (Jiang, et al. 2009). It is spoken in the counties of Mojiang, Jiangcheng, and Luchun in Yunnan, China.
==Distribution== Ximoluo is spoken mostly in Yayi Township 雅邑乡, south-central [[Mojiang County]], where most of the locals are classified as ethnic Hani, Han, Yi, and Dai (Jiang, et al. 2009:4). There are more than 8,000 Ximoluo people in Yayi Township, in the villages of Yayi 雅邑,<ref>http://www.ynszxc.gov.cn/villagePage/vIndex.aspx?departmentid=178218</ref> Xuka 徐卡,<ref>http://www.ynszxc.gov.cn/villagePage/vIndex.aspx?departmentid=178323</ref> Nanwen 南温,<ref>http://www.ynszxc.gov.cn/villagePage/vIndex.aspx?departmentid=178296</ref> Zuoxi 座细,<ref>http://www.ynszxc.gov.cn/villagePage/vIndex.aspx?departmentid=178209</ref> and Nanniwan 南泥湾,<ref>http://www.ynszxc.gov.cn/villagePage/vIndex.aspx?departmentid=178284</ref> and also smaller numbers in Xialuopu 下洛浦,<ref>http://www.ynszxc.gov.cn/villagePage/vIndex.aspx?departmentid=178223</ref> Baga 巴嘎,<ref>http://www.ynszxc.gov.cn/villagePage/vIndex.aspx?departmentid=178231</ref> and Bali 坝利.<ref>http://www.ynszxc.gov.cn/villagePage/vIndex.aspx?departmentid=267473</ref>
