{{Infobox language |name=Paza |altname=Phusang |states=[[Laos]] |region= |ethnicity=[[Akha people|Akha]] |speakers=2,100 |date=2010 |ref=<ref name="numeral">http://lingweb.eva.mpg.de/numeral/Paza.htm (Nathan Badenoch 2010)</ref> |familycolor=Sino-Tibetan |fam2=([[Tibeto-Burman languages|Tibeto-Burman]]) |fam3=[[Lolo–Burmese languages|Lolo–Burmese]] |fam4=[[Loloish languages|Loloish]] |fam5=[[Southern Loloish languages|Southern]] |fam6=Sila |iso3=none |glotto=none }}
'''Paza''' (Phusang, Phosang, Phousang, Basar, Bazar, (Pusa?); autonym: ''{{IPA|pa˧za˧}}'') is a [[Loloish language]] of northern [[Laos]]. Paza speakers consist of 2,100 people distributed in 8 villages of Ban Phusang Mai, Muang [[Samphanh District|Samphan]], [[Phongsaly]], and 1 village in [[Oudomxay]].<ref name="numeral"/> It is documented as "Phusang" in Kato (2008), which has a brief word list of the language collected from Phusangkao village, [[Samphanh District|Samphan District]].
==References== {{reflist}}
*Kato, Takashi. 2008. ''Linguistic Survey of Tibeto-Burman languages in Lao P.D.R.'' Tokyo: Institute for the Study of Languages and Cultures of Asia and Africa (ILCAA).
